    geo_model_ready:"✅ multilingual-e5-large ready",
    geo_model_error:"❌ Failed to load model: ",
    geo_h_two:"Two readings of this space",
    geo_two_sub:"The geometry above is not just mathematics. A writer and a philosopher described this space long before anyone could compute it.",
    geo_borges_num:"Borges · 1941",
    geo_borges_h:"The Library and the Compass",
    geo_borges_p1:"In <em>The Library of Babel</em>, Jorge Luis Borges imagined a library containing every possible book — every combination of letters, in every language. Its librarians spend their lives searching for one meaningful page, and die without finding it. The library contains everything, and is therefore worth nothing: <strong>information without selection is noise</strong>.",
    geo_borges_p2:"The embedding space above is that library, made continuous. Every possible sentence in every language has coordinates here, and almost all of them are gibberish. What makes the space usable is not its content but its <em>index</em> — a function that can tell meaning from noise.",
    geo_borges_p3:"That is what Buchenberg builds. Five models generate candidates near the point where the meaning of the original lives; cosine similarity and a blind judge measure which candidate landed closest. The librarian finally has a compass. It is also why the judge carries 60% of the final score: the scoring function is a more valuable artifact than any single translation it selects.",
    geo_borges_p4:"Borges made the point twice. In <em>Pierre Menard, Author of the Quixote</em> (1939), a modern writer recreates Cervantes word for word — and the identical text means something entirely different. Form does not carry meaning; context does. Menard is the problem of translation, stated precisely, fourteen years before philosophy caught up.",
    geo_witt_num:"Wittgenstein · 1953",
    geo_witt_h:"Meaning as Use",
    geo_witt_p1:"The young Wittgenstein of the <em>Tractatus</em> (1921) believed meaning was logical form: a sentence mirrors reality, and translation preserves the mirror. The late Wittgenstein of the <em>Philosophical Investigations</em> (1953) corrected himself: <strong>the meaning of a word is its use in the language</strong>. Concepts are held together not by a common essence but by <em>family resemblance</em> — overlapping similarities, like the faces of one family.",
    geo_witt_p2:"The scatter plot above is family resemblance, quantified. The embedding model learns meaning from nothing but use — the company each word keeps across billions of sentences. Cosine similarity is the degree of resemblance between two members of the family; the UMAP clusters you can see are families of meaning, drawn by no one.",
    geo_witt_p3:"The whole pipeline follows the late Wittgenstein. Back-translation tests whether <em>meaning</em> survives the round trip, not whether form does. And the judge’s naturalness score measures exactly what he called competence in a language game: does this sentence live comfortably in the life of the target language?",
    geo_footer_note:"Edwin Abbott’s <em>Flatland</em> — book 21 in this corpus — completes the trio: Abbott supplies the geometry, Borges the semantics, Wittgenstein the bridge between them. Buchenberg translates literature with a technology whose problems were stated most precisely by literature itself.",
